 year'|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Doctors in Wales have written a joint letter to First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] urging him to ban the use of [[Holiday cottage|second homes]] during the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-52055456|title=Ban using second homes, doctors urge Drakeford|first=Felicity|last=Evans|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*23 April\n**The number of recorded deaths increases by 616 to 18,738.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-23/coronavirus-deaths-cases-uk-thursday-scotland-wales-northernireland-england-latest/|title=UK hospital coronavirus death toll rises to 18,738 as 616 more lives lost|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n**The first human trials of a coronavirus vaccine in Europe begin in Oxford.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52394485 Coronavirus: First patients injected in UK vaccine trial] 23 April 2020 ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 23 April 2020</ref>\n**A study involving 20,000 households in England, coordinated by the [[Office for National Statistics (United Kingdom)|Office for National Statistics]], will track the progress of COVID-19 and seek to better understand infection and immunity levels, with volunteers asked to provide nose and throat swabs on a regular basis to determine whether they have the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52390970|title=Virus study to track infection and immunity levels|date=23 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Matt Hancock states that daily test capacity has reached 51,000, and announces that all key workers and members of their households are now eligible for COVID-19 tests and will be able to book tests through the government website from the following day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52401398|title=Essential workers in England to get virus tests|date=23 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Tests will be conducted at drive-through centres or using home testing kit